snippet.textDisplay:
That engine was heavily worked over, and had zero factory parts in the bottom end... Carrillo's and a forged crank/pistons, barely any in the top end. And the 6xx horsepower was at 8 psi, the car had a boost controller that allowed it to be increased to around 1bar , which put it at over 1000hp at the wheels.
And changing those ancient Garrett's, for say... 2 gtx3076r's would change performance characteristics drastically, as turbos have came a LONG way. In the early days turbos were hated on for their very perceptible lag.
snippet.textOriginal:

It was a very good choice given what was available in the 80s; although, who would want an auto in an 80s supercar?

snippet.textDisplay: No mention that the engine is TRANSVERSE mounted, like a Fiero? My dad and I took a tour of the Vector factory in 1991, I'm pretty sure all 20 cars were still there in various states of assembly... I don't remember the engine being transverse mounted, that's very unusual for a supercar, but I was only 19 at the time.

snippet.textDisplay: I remember reading about the Vector W2 in Car and Driver magazine back in 1980 or so.  The W2 is the concept car prototype for the W8.  I remember a statement by Wiegert that he intended for the driver and passenger seats to be close together, presumably to make it easier to fool around.  One thing that caught my attention in this video is the rear trunk latch handle, which is the same used on the Fiat X1/9.
